sect1.para:
Immigrants to Western countries were initially scattered, but many have joined family and clan members in urban centers throughout the US, especially Minneapolis–St. Paul, Minnesota. Many have built prosperous lives, opened businesses, and taken advantage of educational opportunities. In some Minnesota high schools and community colleges, more than half the students are Somali. Residual conflict persists in their new homes between members of different clans still at war in Somalia. Diversity among Somalis varies according to acculturation and the variant characteristics of culture (see Chap. 

                  2

            ).
